            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>How this Simple Harmonic Motion calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool models one-dimensional simple harmonic motion (SHM)
                using the standard cosine form \[ x(t) = A \cos(\omega t +
                \varphi), \] where:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>A</strong> is the amplitude (maximum displacement),
                </li>
                <li><strong>ω</strong> is the angular frequency in rad/s,</li>
                <li><strong>φ</strong> is the initial phase at time t = 0,</li>
                <li><strong>t</strong> is the time variable.</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>From mass and spring constant to angular frequency</h3>
              <p>
                For an ideal horizontal mass–spring system with mass \(m\) and
                spring constant \(k\), the angular frequency is
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">\[ \omega = \sqrt{\frac{k}{m}}. \]</div>
              <p>
                The calculator converts your inputs to SI units (kg, N/m, m)
                internally, computes \(\omega\), and then derives:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Frequency:</strong> \( f = \dfrac{\omega}{2\pi} \)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Period:</strong> \( T = \dfrac{1}{f} =
                  \dfrac{2\pi}{\omega} \)
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Displacement, velocity, and acceleration</h3>
              <p>
                Once \(A\), \(\omega\), \(\varphi\), and \(t\) are known, the
                kinematic quantities follow directly:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ \begin{aligned} x(t) &= A \cos(\omega t + \varphi), \\ v(t)
                &= \frac{dx}{dt} = -A\omega \sin(\omega t + \varphi), \\ a(t) &=
                \frac{d^2x}{dt^2} = -A\omega^2 \cos(\omega t + \varphi).
                \end{aligned} \]
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator evaluates these expressions at your chosen time
                \(t\) and reports the results in the same length units you
                selected for the amplitude.
              </p>

              <h3>Energy in simple harmonic motion</h3>
              <p>
                When both mass \(m\) and spring constant \(k\) are provided, the
                total mechanical energy of the oscillator is
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ E = \frac{1}{2}kA^2 = \frac{1}{2}m\omega^2 A^2. \]
              </div>
              <p>At any time \(t\), the potential and kinetic energies are:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ \begin{aligned} U(t) &= \frac{1}{2}k x(t)^2, \\ K(t) &=
                \frac{1}{2}m v(t)^2. \end{aligned} \]
              </div>
              <p>
                In ideal SHM (no damping), \(E = U + K\) remains constant over
                time. Small numerical differences in the calculator are due to
                rounding.
              </p>

              <h2>Typical examples</h2>
              <h3>1. Mass–spring oscillator</h3>
              <p>
                Suppose a 0.50&nbsp;kg mass is attached to a spring with \(k =
                20\ \text{N/m}\) and pulled 0.10&nbsp;m from equilibrium, then
                released from rest.
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  \(m = 0.50\ \text{kg}\), \(k = 20\ \text{N/m}\), \(A = 0.10\
                  \text{m}\), \(\varphi = 0\).
                </li>
                <li>
                  \(\omega = \sqrt{k/m} = \sqrt{20 / 0.5} = \sqrt{40} \approx
                  6.32\ \text{rad/s}\).
                </li>
                <li>
                  \(T = 2\pi / \omega \approx 0.995\ \text{s}\), \(f \approx
                  1.00\ \text{Hz}\).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Total energy \(E = \tfrac{1}{2}kA^2 = 0.5 \times 20 \times
                  0.1^2 = 0.10\ \text{J}\).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Enter these values in the calculator, choose a time (for example
                \(t = 0.25\ \text{s}\)), and you will see the instantaneous
                displacement, velocity, acceleration, and energy split.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Using measured period or frequency</h3>
              <p>
                In experiments, you often measure the period \(T\) or frequency
                \(f\) directly. Use the “Angular frequency (ω, A, φ)” tab:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Enter \(T\) or \(\omega\) (the calculator will convert \(T\)
                  to \(\omega\) via \(\omega = 2\pi/T\)).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Provide the amplitude and phase (for example, from initial
                  conditions).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Compute to obtain \(x(t)\), \(v(t)\), and \(a(t)\) without
                  needing \(m\) or \(k\).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Key properties of simple harmonic motion</h2>
              <h3>1. Restoring force proportional to displacement</h3>
              <p>SHM arises when the restoring force is linear:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ F = -kx \quad \Rightarrow \quad m\frac{d^2x}{dt^2} = -kx. \]
              </div>
              <p>
                Solving this differential equation leads to sinusoidal motion
                with constant amplitude and period.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Period independent of amplitude (for ideal SHM)</h3>
              <p>
                For a perfect mass–spring system, the period \[ T =
                2\pi\sqrt{\frac{m}{k}} \] does not depend on the amplitude
                \(A\). Real systems deviate from this when the spring is
                non-linear or damping is significant.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Phase and initial conditions</h3>
              <p>
                The phase \(\varphi\) encodes the initial position and velocity:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  If the mass starts at \(x(0) = A\) with zero velocity, then
                  \(\varphi = 0\).
                </li>
                <li>
                  If it starts at \(x(0) = 0\) moving in the positive direction,
                  then \(\varphi = -\pi/2\).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                You can use the phase input (in degrees or radians) to match
                your specific initial conditions.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>
              <h3>What is simple harmonic motion used for?</h3>
              <p>
                SHM is a fundamental model in physics and engineering. It
                describes small oscillations of springs, pendulums (for small
                angles), molecular vibrations, AC circuits (via analogies), and
                many mechanical and electrical resonators.
              </p>

              <h3>Can this calculator handle damped or driven oscillations?</h3>
              <p>
                No. This tool models <em>undamped, unforced</em> simple harmonic
                motion only. For damped or driven systems, the equations of
                motion include additional terms and the motion is no longer
                purely sinusoidal.
              </p>

              <h3>What units should I use?</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Mass: kg or g (internally converted to kg).</li>
                <li>
                  Spring constant: N/m or N/cm (internally converted to N/m).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Amplitude: m, cm, or mm (results are reported in the same
                  length unit).
                </li>
                <li>Time: seconds.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Keeping units consistent ensures physically meaningful results.
